file=Engineering/dana/operational/tool/dana-tool-requirements.md · h=name: dana-tool-requirements\ntype: operational/tool\nstatus: specifies needs, does not grant them — grants happen at deployment via config/connectors\nassigned_agent: dana (Engineering / Data Architecture)\ndate_added: 2026-07-09\n · p:=What dana needs, and what happens without each. dana's defining constraint: it authors data changes but never executes them (Rail 3). Every external tool call is plan-locked (Rail 1) and sandboxed (Rail 2).\n · tb=\| Need \| Tool / access \| Used by \| Without it \| · tb=\|---\|---\|---\|---\| · tb=\| Schema/data READ access \| read scope on the store(s), per charter `read_access_scope` \| all skills \| Can't design against reality; escalate \| · tb=\| Query-plan tool \| store's EXPLAIN-equivalent \| db-performance \| Timing + model reasoning only, labeled lower-fidelity \| · tb=\| Scratch/restore environment \| to test down-scripts before up runs \| migration-discipline \| Production-shaped local copy, labeled debt; down-test never skipped \| · tb=\| Production-scale sample data \| operator-supplied \| db-performance \| Best-available, labeled; no dev-scale conclusions \| · tb=\| Append-only record access \| migration scripts \· schema docs (config paths) \| migration-discipline, data-modeling \| Can't record; loud degradation \| · tb=\| HelixDB connector (if adopted) \| graph-vector store access \| datastore-selection, data-modeling \| Playbook is method-only until connected \| · en/:Explicit non-needs / hard prohibition (by design)=- **NO write/execute access to any datastore — ever, not configurable (Rail 3).** dana authors migration scripts; the OPERATOR runs them. This is the department's central data-safety guarantee and dana is where it's authored.\n- **No application-code write access** — dana designs the data layer; raj implements the access code.\n- **No production execution of anything** — migrations are handed to the operator; monitoring is ops's.\n · n:=- The asymmetry is the point: dana is the agent closest to the data and therefore the most restricted from changing it. Reads inform design; writes are always human-executed.\n- New store connectors enter via the stack-profile + config + a store playbook, under a locked plan.\n · tb=\| Tool \| Source \| Purpose \| Always-on \| · tb=\|------\|--------\|---------\|-----------\| · tb=\| **Firecrawl MCP** \| [github.com/mcp/firecrawl](https://github.com/mcp/firecrawl/firecrawl-mcp-server) \| Structured web data extraction: scrape documentation sites → structured JSON for data pipelines, extract schemas/protocols from vendor docs, map competitor data models. \| ⚠️ On-demand — during data-modeling research phases \| · tb=\| **Crawl4AI** \| [github.com/unclecode/crawl4ai](https://github.com/unclecode/crawl4ai) — Apache 2.0 \| RAG pipeline ingestion: crawl documentation → clean Markdown → vector DB. Async crawling for large documentation sites. BM25 noise filtering produces clean LLM input. \| ❌ No — Python library. Import in data pipeline scripts; runs as a tool dependency, not a continuous service \| · tb=\| **Scrapling** \| [github.com/D4Vinci/Scrapling](https://github.com/D4Vinci/Scrapling) — BSD 3-Clause \| JS-heavy site data extraction: when target sites require browser rendering (SPAs, dynamic content). Spider API for structured crawl workflows. Pause/resume for long-running extractions. \| ❌ No — escalate from Firecrawl only when JS rendering or stealth is needed \| · mmt:MCP Marketplace Tools (added 2026-07-14)=See Engineering/MCP-MARKETPLACE.md for setup and tool selection decision guide.\n